2ï¸âƒ£ What is Continuous Integration, Continuous Delivery, and Continuous Deployment?
ğŸ”¹ Continuous Integration (CI) â†’ Developers push code frequently, and automated tests run to validate changes (e.g., GitHub Actions, Jenkins, GitLab CI).
ğŸ”¹ Continuous Delivery (CD) â†’ Code is automatically built, tested, and deployed to a staging environment but requires manual approval for production.
ğŸ”¹ Continuous Deployment (CD) â†’ Fully automated pipeline where code changes go live without manual intervention.

ğŸ“Œ Example:

CI: A developer pushes code â†’ Automated tests run.
CD (Delivery): After passing tests, the build is deployed to a staging environment for approval.
CD (Deployment): If automated, the changes go live without manual approval.
3ï¸âƒ£ What is the difference between ALB and NLB?
Feature	ALB (Application Load Balancer)	NLB (Network Load Balancer)
Protocol	Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS)	Layer 4 (TCP/UDP)
Routing	Path-based, host-based	Direct to IP/port
Performance	Slightly slower (more processing)	Faster (low latency)
Use case	Web applications, API Gateway	Low-latency apps, gaming, VoIP
Example	Routing requests to microservices	Handling millions of requests quickly
